snippet.textDisplay: Hey Dr Mike, I’m an Australian and am  little perplexed by the American healthcare system. I’m wondering if you can help me understand? I was in travelling around the US recently and got a throat infection. I went to a doctor and the 20 minute consultation to get some antibiotics cost me $700USD (luckily I had travel insurance). Is this normal?? In Australia this would either be free (fully government funded through Medicare) or there would be a small gap payment ($30-$40USD), depending on which doctor you go see. I’ve also heard stories of people being bankrupted by surgery/hospital stays, which is a totally foreign concept to an Aussie. How does the funding system work for you guys? Medicare? Obamacare?? Health insurance?? Can people afford to visit the doctor? Thanks Dr Mike!

snippet.textDisplay: Hi Dr. Mike! My son is 13 months old. Since 3 months old, he has taken Propranolol every 12 hours for a hemangioma above his eye. Recently the ophthalmology and vascular malformation docs have told us to reduce his dose to once every 24 hours. Additionally, they have told us that it’s fine to hold the meds if he is wheezing, or that if we forget a dose it’s no big deal. My mother and my mother in law are/were both nurses, and keep telling me it can be harmful to abruptly quit a beta blocker because it could mess with the heart rhythm (at least that’s how I heard it, not being a medical professional). I have asked my sons doctors about this, and they reassured me that since he’s not taking the beta blocker to treat a heart issue, it would be fine to stop the medicine abruptly if needed. What do you think about this?

snippet.textDisplay: Hi Dr. Mike...im 4.5 yrs post op from gastric bypass (7/2015). - i became pregnant w/a blighted ovum that my body failed to miscarry after i was 12wks pregnant (according to my LMP) . Had a d&c, developed a benign endometrial polyp 2months later, had another d&c. By aug2017 i became pregnant again. Late 2nd trimester and for my entire third trimester, i kept getting severe abdominal pain, but the ob docs could never figure out why. 2wks postpartum, i developed a life threatening condition called intussusception of the small bowel (ileal to jejunal). I ended up losing 10inches of bowel bc by the time the surgeons opened me up , my bowels at the site of the obstruction became necrotic. I was advised to never become pregnant again. The docs think that bc i had gastric bypass surgery (i lost 100 pounds), i was at an increased risk for a small bowel obstruction so they think that since my uterus spent months putting pressure on my bowels, the moment it started to contract to return to its normal state, my bowels went haywire and couldnt adapt appropriately. For that reason, i was told to never get pregnant again bc i am now at double the risk of developing intussusception again. Do you agree with these docs? Is it too risky to go through another pregnancy? I only have 1 child so it was hard thinking that i cant give my child a sibling bc its much to dangerous for me to physically bear another child.

snippet.textDisplay:
It turns out that smartphone features like Night Light and Night Shift — which tint the screen to reduce blue light and help users fall asleep — don’t actually help users fall asleep. In fact, tinting your screen may actually be worse.
In research conducted on mice, the university of Manchester found that colour-sensing cone cells in the eye may be more responsive to yellow light than the response of melanopsin to blue light. In other words, using your phone in night mode may actually increase the stimuli from your eyes telling your brain it isn’t time for sleep.
